replies.comment info:
@Samantha Weber 
Hi Samantha, 
I loved your catchy headline 'Is Hurricane Milton the Cause or Effect of the Gulf of Mexico’s rapid temperature change?'. This is really interesting to consider since the effects of climate change are apparent in several other extreme weather changes occurring in society such as an increase or irregularity of mud slides, forest fires, flash floods, and of course climate changes. You also made a very interesting point considering whether or how hurricanes can also impact climate change events, and this is very important to consider as well.

@Perry the Platypus 

Hey Perry!

You had some great observations about this graph, and I also like how you related your headline back to recent events with hurricane Milton and Helene! Additionally, I believe I may be able to offer some insight in regards to your question! First of all, I can very much agree that the population of the world is an important factor to earth's temperature and is often an aspect that is looked over when it comes to earth's conditions. I believe that over time, as our population has continued to climb especially with the amonut of fossil fuels the world consumes in conjunction with how many people are consuming those resources every day, the earth's temperature has experienced a significant increase and back in the day when our population was much smaller, this consumption of fossil fuels was most definately more controlled an much less of a problem.

@Brayden Scheffers 

Hey Brayden!

You have made some great observations and I appreciate that you still took the time to check out this graph even if hurricanes are not too big of a concern in your area it's always great to know what is going on outside your own state. Additionally, in regards to your question about whether this data could be used to predict when hurricanes may appear is a great question/possibility and I believe that this kind of data is something that meteorologists have to pay a lot of attention to to make their forecasts and as we move into the future, this will only continue to grow in importance especially with the effects of global warming, we may be able to expect much stronger storms in the years to come.
